Data

In this project, you will explore a dataset that contains information about movies, including ratings, budget, gross revenue and other attributes. It was prepared by Dr. Guy Lebanon, and here is his description of the dataset:

The file movies_merged contains a dataframe with the same name that has 40K rows and 39 columns. Each row represents a movie title and each column represents a descriptor such as Title, Actors, and Budget. I collected the data by querying IMDb’s API (see www.omdbapi.com) and joining it with a separate dataset of movie budgets and gross earnings (unknown to you). The join key was the movie title. This data is available for personal use, but IMDb’s terms of service do not allow it to be used for commercial purposes or for creating a competing repository.

Objective

Your goal is to investigate the relationship between the movie descriptors and the box office success of movies, as represented by the variable Gross. This task is extremely important as it can help a studio decide which titles to fund for production, how much to bid on produced movies, when to release a title, how much to invest in marketing and PR, etc. This information is most useful before a title is released, but it is still very valuable after the movie is already released to the public (for example it can affect additional marketing spend or how much a studio should negotiate with on-demand streaming companies for “second window” streaming rights).

2. Process Runtime column

The variable Runtime represents the length of the title as a string. Write R code to convert it to a numeric value (in minutes) and replace df$Runtime with the new numeric column.

#options(warn = -1)
## case 1 hr, case 2 hr/min, case 3 min, case 4 N/A
##iterates over each element and changes accordingly
minRun = c()
for(i in seq(df2$Runtime)){
   runtime = strsplit(df2$Runtime[i], ' ')[[1]]
    
      if (length(runtime) ==  2){ 
        
           #case 3 only minutes
          
          if(runtime[2] == "min")
          {minRun = suppressWarnings(c(minRun, as.integer(runtime[1])))}
          
          # case 1 hours
          
          else{minRun = suppressWarnings(c(minRun, (as.integer(runtime[1])) * 60))}
      }
   
      # case 2 hours/minutes
   
      else if( length((runtime) == 4)) {
        minRun = suppressWarnings(c(minRun, as.integer(runtime[1]) * 60  + as.integer(runtime[3])))
      }
   
       # case 1 N/A
      else minRun = c(minRun, NA)
      
     
      
      
}
#replace original runtime data.
 df2$Runtime <- minRun

The variable Awards describes nominations and awards in text format. Convert it to 2 numeric columns, the first capturing the number of wins, and the second capturing nominations. Replace the Awards column with these new columns, and then study the relationship of Gross revenue with respect to them.

Note: The format of the Awards column is not standard; you may have to use regular expressions to find the relevant values. Try your best to process them, and you may leave the ones that don’t have enough information as NAs or set them to 0s.

# TODO: Convert Awards to 2 numeric columns: wins and nominations
#initialize an empty data frame for awards and nominations
awardsDF = data.frame(matrix(ncol = 2, nrow = dim(df2)[1] ))
colnames(awardsDF) = c("win", "nomination")
#loop over every element in the data
for (i in 1:dim(awardsDF)[1]){
  
  #split phrases into words
  disambig = unlist(strsplit(df2[i, "Awards"], split=" "))
 
  
  if(length(disambig) < 2) next
  
  for (j in 1:(length(disambig) - 1)){
    
    if (grepl("w",disambig[j+1])) {
      numWins = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(disambig[j]))
      awardsDF[i, "win"] = numWins
      
    }
    
    
    if (grepl("n",disambig[j+1])) {
        numNominations = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(disambig[j]))
        awardsDF[i, "nomination"] = numNominations
    }
  }
    
  
}
df2["win"] <-awardsDF[1]
df2["nomination"] <- awardsDF[2]

Q: How did you construct your conversion mechanism? How many rows had valid/non-zero wins or nominations?

A: We want to define two new colums in our dataset, for award and for nomination each. We then loop ovr the entire df2$Awards column and extract the numeric value preceding the word awards or the word nomination into their respective column.

Q: Unexpected insight.

A: Plotting the most common first names of actors as a frequency shows that the first names of actors are typically biblical western male names, indicating that the data sourced is heavily skewed towards western produced movies, or even that the industry itself is skewed towards casting male leads with biblical names. Perhaps this could be read as this type of actor would be a safe investment for the studio.

Another interpretation is that perhaps in the wake of the success of movies such as Wonder Woman and Black Panther, indicators are present that the movie trends represented in this data are ready to be broken.

This data also probably not accounting for actors in asian markets, or perhaps is dealing with a serious skew in translating their names into English character. To typify the potential for such error, take the japanese katakana ゆ, which represents a common female name. It is pronounced “You”, and common spellings vary between Yu, Yū, Yuu, and perhaps even more further into Yuki or Yukari if using hiragana or kanji letter systems. The one japanese name, could produce 6 english results. Apart from the issues presented when translating between different language systems, there is an increased probability of incorrect data entry. With these complications, It could be a difficult, but economically rewarding task to create advacned methods for integrating names and titles properly between different language systems.
